libraries.name: Bibliothèque Nationale de France
libraries.description: The Bibliothèque Nationale de France is the national library of France, located in Paris. It is one of the largest libraries in the world, with over 14 million books and other documents in its collections. The library has several locations throughout the city, including the François Mitterrand site in the 13th arrondissement and the Richelieu-Louvois site in the 2nd arrondissement.

libraries.name: Bibliothèque Mazarine
libraries.description: The Bibliothèque Mazarine is the oldest public library in France, founded in 1643. It is located in the 6th arrondissement of Paris, near the Jardin du Luxembourg. The library's collections include over 600,000 books and manuscripts, covering a wide range of subjects.

libraries.name: Bibliothèque Sainte-Geneviève
libraries.description: The Bibliothèque Sainte-Geneviève is a public research library in Paris, located in the 5th arrondissement. It was founded in the 18th century to house the collections of the Abbey of St. Genevieve, which was the patron saint of Paris. The library's collections include over 2 million books, manuscripts, and other documents.

libraries.name: Bibliothèque Forney
libraries.description: The Bibliothèque Forney is a public library in Paris that specializes in the arts and crafts. It is located in the Marais district of the city, and has over 100,000 books, manuscripts, prints, and other materials in its collections. The library also hosts exhibitions and events related to its areas of focus.
